The Army's surgeon general on Thursday criticized stories in The Washington Post disclosing problems at Walter Reed Army Medical Centersaying the series unfairly characterized the living conditions and care for soldiers recuperating from wounds at the hospital's facilities.
Defense Secretary Robert Gates says people found to have been responsible for allowing substandard living conditions for soldier outpatients at Walter Reed Army Medical Center in Washington will beheld accountablealthough so far no one in the Army chain of command has offered to resign.
Gates spoke to reporters after visiting the medical compound' housing and in the medical bureaucracy at Walter Reed.
